example.p:
We compute the desired derivative by just substituting the function of interest into the formal definition of the derivative.


  f'(a) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(a+h) - f(a)}{h} && \text{(the definition)}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{c - c}{h} && \text{(substituted in the function)}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} 0 &&\text{(simplified things)}

  &= 0

Again, we compute the derivative of g by just substituting the function of interest into the formal definition of the derivative and then evaluating the resulting limit.


  g'(a) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{g(a+h) - g(a)}{h}
                  && \text{(the definition)}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(a+h) - a}{h}
                   && \text{(substituted in the function)}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{h}{h} && \text{(simplified things)}

  &= \lim_{h \to 0} 1 && \text{(simplified a bit more)}

  &= 1

ul.li:
So let us write the definition of the derivative


  f'(a) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}


and then translate it to the function names and variables at hand:


  h'(a) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{h(a+h)-h(a)}{h}

Now we are ready to begin. Substituting in what the function h is,


 h'(a) &= \lim_{\De t \to 0} \frac{(a+\De t)^2-a^2}{\De t}

  &= \lim_{\De t \to 0} \frac{a^2+2a\,\De t+\De t^2-a^2}{\De t}
		   && \big(\text{just squared out $(a+\De t)^2$}\big)

  &= \lim_{\De t \to 0} \frac{2a\,\De t+\De t^2}{\De t}

  &= \lim_{\De t \to 0} (2a +\De t)

  &= 2a

subsection.p:
We can do this more generally and tweak the derivative at a specific point a to
obtain the derivative as a function of x. We replace


  f'(a) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}

with

  f'(x) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}


which gives us the following definition

example.p:
Let f(x) = \frac{1}{x} and compute its derivative with respect to x  think  carefully about where the derivative exists.



	Our first step is to write down the definition of the derivative  at this stage, we know of no other strategy for computing derivatives.


	f'(x)&=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}
		 && \text{(the definition)}





	And now we substitute in the function and compute the limit.


	f'(x)&=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}
		 && \text{(the definition)}

	&=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{1}{h}\left[\frac{1}{x+h}-\frac{1}{x}\right]
		 && \text{(substituted in the function)}

	&=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{1}{h}\ \frac{x-(x+h)}{x(x+h)}
		 && \text{(wrote over a common denominator)}

	&=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{1}{h}\ \frac{-h}{x(x+h)}
		 && \text{(started cleanup)}

	&=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0} \frac{-1}{x(x+h)}

	&=-\frac{1}{x^2}





	Notice that the original function f(x)=\frac{1}{x} was not defined at  x=0 and  the derivative is also not defined  at x=0. This does happen more  generally  if f(x) is not defined at a particular point x=a, then the derivative  will not exist at that point either.

ul.li:
So again we start with the definition of derivative and go from there:


f'(a)
&=\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}
 =\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a}}{x-a}

For the first, review Example, which concerned taking a limit involving square-roots, and recall that  we used  multiplication by the conjugate there:


  \frac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a}}{x-a}
  &= \frac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a}}{x-a} \times
			  \frac{\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a}}{\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a}}
  && \Big(\text{multiplication by
		$1=\frac{\text{conjugate}}{\text{conjugate}}$}\Big)

  &=\frac{(\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a})(\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a})}
						{(x-a)(\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a})}

  &= \frac{x-a}{(x-a)(\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a})}
  && \big(\text{since $(A-B)(A+B) = A^2-B^2$)}\,\big)

  &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a}}

Alternatively, we can arrive at  \frac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a}}{x-a}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a}}  by using almost the same trick to factor the denominator. Just set A=\sqrt{x} and  B=\sqrt{a} in  A^2 - B^2 = (A-B)(A+B)   to get


  x - a &= (\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a})(\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a})


and then substitute this little fact into our expression


  \frac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a}}{x-a}
  &=\frac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a}}{(\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a})(\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a})}
  & \text{(now cancel common factors)}

  &=\frac{1}{(\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a})}

Once we know that \frac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a}}{x-a}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a}},  we  can take the limit we need:


f'(a)
&=\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{a}}{x-a}

&
=\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{1}{\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{a}}

&
=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{a}}

example.p:
Compute the derivative, f'(a), of the function f(x)=|x| at the point  x=a.





	We should start this example by recalling the definition of |x| (we  saw this back in Example):


	  |x| &= \begin{cases}
		 -x & \text{ if } x \lt 0\\
		 0 & \text{ if } x=0\\
		 x & \text{ if }x \gt 0.
		 \end{cases}


	It is definitely not just chop off the minus sign.








	This breaks our computation of the derivative into 3 cases depending on  whether x is positive, negative or zero.



	Assume x \gt 0. Then


	  \diff{f}{x}
	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}

	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{|x+h|-|x|}{h}


	Since x \gt 0 and we are interested in the behaviour of this function  as h \to 0 we can assume h is much smaller than x. This means x+h \gt 0 and  so |x+h|=x+h.

	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{x+h-x}{h}

	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{h}{h} = 1 &\text{as expected}





	Assume x \lt 0. Then


	  \diff{f}{x}
	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}

	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{|x+h|-|x|}{h}


	Since x \lt 0 and we are interested in the behaviour of this function  as h \to 0 we can assume h is much smaller than x. This means x+h \lt 0 and  so |x+h|=-(x+h).

	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{-(x+h)-(-x)}{h}

	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{-h}{h} = -1





	When x=0 we have


	  f'(0)
	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{f(0+h)-f(0)}{h}

	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{|0+h|-|0|}{h}

	  &= \lim_{h\to0} \frac{|h|}{h}


	To proceed we need to know if h \gt 0 or h \lt 0, so we must use one-sided limits.  The limit from above is:


	  \lim_{h \to 0^+} \frac{|h|}{h}
	  &=
	  \lim_{h \to 0^+} \frac{h}{h} &\text{since } h \gt 0, |h|=h

	&= 1

	Whereas, the limit from below is:

	  \lim_{h \to 0^-} \frac{|h|}{h} &=
	\lim_{h \to 0^-} \frac{-h}{h} &\text{since } h \lt 0, |h|= -h

	&= -1


	Since the one-sided limits differ, the limit as h\to 0 does not exist. And  thus the derivative does not exist as x=0.


In summary:


  \diff{}{x} |x| &= \begin{cases}
                     -1 & \text{if } x \lt 0 \\
                     DNE & \text{if } x=0 \\
                     1 & \text{if } x \gt 0
                    \end{cases}

does not have a tangent line at (0,0). Not surprisingly, when a=0 and h tends to 0 with h \gt 0,


\frac{H(a+h)-H(a)}{h}
=\frac{H(h)-H(0)}{h}
 =\frac{1}{h}


blows up. The same sort of computation shows that  f'(a) cannot possibly exist whenever the function f is not continuous at a. We will formalize, and prove, this statement  in Theorem , below.

has the yaxis as its tangent line at (0,0). So we would expect that f'(0) does not exist. Let's check. With a=0,


f'(a)= \lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}
=\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{f(h)-f(0)}{h}
 =\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{h^{1/3}}{h}
 =\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{1}{h^{2/3}}
 =DNE


as expected.

The pointy thing at the origin is called a cusp. The graph of y=f(x) does not have a tangent line at (0,0) and, correspondingly, f'(0) does not exist because


\lim_{h\rightarrow 0^+}\frac{f(h)-f(0)}{h}
 =\lim_{h\rightarrow 0^+}\frac{\sqrt{|h|}}{h}
 =\lim_{h\rightarrow 0^+}\frac{1}{\sqrt{h}}
 =DNE
